\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {1}{\ignorespaces \textbf  {The central result.} Precursor alarm time vs.\ emergence time. Blue: the calibration fleet (30 seeds, config A) --- Spearman $\rho =0.977$. The dashed line and band are the \emph  {frozen} rule (event $=$ alarm $+\,975\pm 150$). Red diamonds with bars: the blind gate --- 10 fresh seeds on a never-seen configuration (wider model, sparser repetition), scored once against the frozen rule: 10/10{} covered. Negatives (18 manufactured capability-blocked runs, not shown) produced zero false alarms.}}{3}{figure.1}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:forecast}{{1}{3}{\textbf {The central result.} Precursor alarm time vs.\ emergence time. Blue: the calibration fleet (30 seeds, config A) --- Spearman $\rho =\wRho $. The dashed line and band are the \emph {frozen} rule (event $=$ alarm $+\,\wConfDelta \pm \wConfQ $). Red diamonds with bars: the blind gate --- 10 fresh seeds on a never-seen configuration (wider model, sparser repetition), scored once against the frozen rule: \wGateCover {} covered. Negatives (18 manufactured capability-blocked runs, not shown) produced zero false alarms}{figure.1}{}}
\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {section}{\numberline {2}Related work}{3}{section.2}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{sec:related}{{2}{3}{Related work}{section.2}{}}
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {2}{\ignorespaces \textbf  {The robustness--false-alarm tradeoff} (MNIST grokking; median warning time at $\leq 5\%$ FA, higher is better). The scalar clock (weight norm) forecasts in-distribution but collapses when interventions decouple the norm from the outcome. The multivariate forecaster that best controls false alarms in-distribution (10{,}400{} steps, 60\%{} of the delay) collapses hardest under shift --- its norm-context features are exactly what the intervention breaks. The bare content probe survives the shift (16{,}400{} steps) but is FA-fragile in corpora with look-alike negatives.}}{4}{figure.2}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:tradeoff}{{2}{4}{\textbf {The robustness--false-alarm tradeoff} (MNIST grokking; median warning time at $\leq 5\%$ FA, higher is better). The scalar clock (weight norm) forecasts in-distribution but collapses when interventions decouple the norm from the outcome. The multivariate forecaster that best controls false alarms in-distribution (\vRoneLead {} steps, \vRoneRel {} of the delay) collapses hardest under shift --- its norm-context features are exactly what the intervention breaks. The bare content probe survives the shift (\vShiftDcos {} steps) but is FA-fragile in corpora with look-alike negatives}{figure.2}{}}
